# FOBOS Positioner GUI

A PySide6 control interface for operating robotic fibre positioners on the FOBOS instrument. Each positioner has two arms (α/β) reaching within an annulus; the UI drives them via manual angle entry or click-to-queue targeting on a live camera feed or 2D grid view.

## Features

- **Manual move** — enter α/β angles directly and go-to.
- **Click-to-queue** — click positioners on the 2D grid or camera view, queue inverse-kinematics targets, swap between the two IK solutions, then send all queued moves in a single batch command.
- **Live camera view** — Allied Vision (vmbpy) feed with a projected positioner overlay, calibrated against physical space. Alternatively can recieve video stream from RPi camera bridge.
- **Mock mode** — run the full UI without hardware attached.
- **Auto-reconnect** — detects dead CAN/camera connections and lets you reconnect from the status bar.

## Requirements

- Python (managed via [`uv`](https://docs.astral.sh/uv/))
- Linux (deployment target) or macOS (development, with Vimba X SDK installed)
- Hardware config at `~/.jaeger.yaml` (CAN@net IP/bus settings) — required only for real hardware (see [jaeger-core](https://github.com/kbwestfall/jaeger-core) for more info on jaeger configuration)
- Allied Vision **Vimba X SDK** installed system-wide for camera support

## Quick start

```bash
# install dependencies
uv sync

# run against real hardware (requires ~/.jaeger.yaml)
uv run main.py

# run without hardware (positioners + camera simulated)
FOBOS_MOCK=1 uv run main.py
```

On first run, the camera view will prompt for calibration (see below) before click-to-move is available in that view.

## Usage guide

### 1. Calibrate the camera (one-time, or after moving the camera)
Click **Calibrate** in the control panel, then click the four corners of the known physical reference rectangle in order: **top-left → top-right → bottom-left → bottom-right**. Calibration is saved to `calibration.json` and reloaded automatically on future launches.

### 2. Queue moves
- Click a positioner once to **select** it.
- Click the selected positioner again to **queue** a move — a dashed blue arm shows the pending target.
- Use **Swap Solution** to toggle between the two IK solutions for that target.
- Repeat for as many positioners as needed.

### 3. Send moves
Click **Send N Targets** to dispatch all queued moves in a single batch command. Positioner state updates (moving → ready/error) appear live in the grid, camera overlay, and status bar.

### 4. Manual single-positioner moves
Enter α/β values directly in the control panel and click the go-to button — bypasses the queue entirely.

### 5. Reconnecting
If the CAN connection or camera drops, the status bar shows a disconnected state. Use **Reconnect FPS** / **Reconnect Camera** to rebuild the connection without restarting the app.

## Project layout

```
fobos-gui/
├── main.py              # entry point
├── app_model.py         # single source of truth for state
├── main_window.py       # wires signals/slots, owns move dispatch
├── helpers/             # kinematics, projection, calibration I/O, drawing
├── workers/             # FPSManager (CAN/asyncio), VimbaWorker (camera), mock hardware
└── widgets/             # camera view, 2D grid, control panel, status bar
```
